"'''Winged Gundark'''" was the nickname among the peers of a<ref name="BTM" /> [[TIE pilot]] in the [[Imperial Navy/Legends|Imperial Navy]] who attained the nickname for<ref name="CCG" /> an impressive number of career [[Death/Legends|kills]]<ref name="CSWE">{{CSWECite|II|402|Obsidian Squadron}}</ref> in high-altitude [[Starfighter combat/Legends|battles]]<ref name="CCG" /> by [[3 ABY/Legends|3 ABY]]. By that [[Standard year/Legends|year's]] [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] [[Occupation of Bespin|occupation]] of the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Bespin/Legends|Bespin]],<ref name="NEC">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]'' dates the [[occupation of Bespin]] to [[3 ABY/Legends|3 ABY]].</ref> Winged Gundark had joined the Imperial [[Obsidian Squadron/Legends|Obsidian Squadron]], flying under the [[Callsign/Legends|call sign]] of [[Obsidian 7]] and [[Pilot/Legends|piloting]] a [[TIE/ln space superiority starfighter/Legends|TIE/LN starfighter]] modified for upper [[Atmosphere/Legends|atmosphere]] maneuvers<ref name="CCG" /> and pursuits.<ref name="BTM" />

Following Bespin's occupation, the [[YT-1300 light freighter/Legends|YT-1300 light freighter]] [[Millennium Falcon/Legends|''Millennium Falcon'']] managed to escape from the planet's [[Cloud City/Legends|Cloud City]],<ref name="ESB">{{Film|V}}</ref> resulting in Obsidian Squadron's pursuit of the [[Freighter/Legends|freighter]] into [[Realspace/Legends|space]].<ref name="CSWE" /> Winged Gundark piloted one of the pursuing TIE/LN [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighters]],<ref name="BTM" /> though the ''Millennium Falcon'' ultimately escaped Obsidian Squadron and Imperial capture.<ref name="ESB" /> At some point, Winged Gundark, accompanied by at least one other TIE/LN starfighter, flew over an astronomical object, with a large [[Starship/Legends|starship]] above the starfighters.<ref name="FFG">{{FFGXW|set=TIE Fighter Expansion Pack|cardname="Winged Gundark"}}</ref> Winged Gundark's nickname was shared with<ref name="CCG" /> the [[Gundark/Legends|gundark]], a large [[Limb/Legends|bipedal]] [[Hair/Legends|furry]] [[Primate/Legends|primate]] [[Species/Legends|species]] from the planet [[Vanqor/Legends|Vanqor]].<ref name="Alien Species">''[[The New Essential Guide to Alien Species]]''</ref>

==Behind the scenes==
The name Winged Gundark was created for the [[1997]] ''[[Cloud City Limited]]'' expansion set of [[Decipher]]'s [[Star Wars Customizable Card Game|''Star Wars'' Customizable Card Game]].<ref name="CCG" /> He would later be mentioned in [[1998]]'s ''[[Star Wars: Behind the Magic]]'', where Obsidian 7 was linked to one of the TIE fighters seen in the [[1980]] [[original trilogy]] film [[Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back|''Star Wars'': Episode V ''The Empire Strikes Back'']], thus also establishing his status as the fighter's offscreen pilot in the film.<ref name="BTM" /> Before the film was released on [[May 21]], 1980,<ref name="Empire Turns 40">{{ThisWeek|6UccH037VQ0|The Empire Strikes Back Turns 40, Queen's Peril Gets a Voice, and More!|sw_url=video/the-empire-strikes-back-turns-40-queen-s-peril-gets-a-voice-and-more}}</ref> Winged Gundark's fighter appeared simultaneously in ''[[The Empire Strikes Back Storybook]]''<ref name="ESB storybook">''[[The Empire Strikes Back Storybook]]''</ref> and the film's [[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back (novelization)|novelization]],<ref name="ESB novel">[[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back (novelization)|''Star Wars Episode V: The Empire Strikes Back'' novelization]]</ref> both released [[April 12]] of the same year.<ref name="Amazon-RandomHouse">{{Amazon|url=Empire-Strikes-Back-Storybook/dp/0394844149|text=The Empire Strikes Back Storybook}} {{C|US hardcover}}</ref><ref name="Year by Year">''[[Star Wars Year By Year: A Visual History, Updated and Expanded Edition]]''</ref>

